      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay thanks that makes more sense. so if the escrow company is the neutral third party, what happens if there is a dispute during the process? like if the seller doesn't fix something they promised to fix before closing, how does the escrow company handle the money?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In the event of a dispute during the escrow process, the escrow company typically has a set of procedures in place to handle such situations. If the seller fails to fulfill their obligations, such as making promised repairs before closing, the buyer can raise the issue with the escrow company. The escrow company will then review the terms of the agreement and the nature of the dispute.\n\nIf the dispute is valid and the seller has not met their obligations, the escrow company may hold the funds in the account until the issue is resolved. This could involve mediation, arbitration, or legal action, depending on the terms of the escrow agreement and the severity of the dispute. The escrow company acts as a neutral party to ensure that the buyer's interests are protected and that the seller fulfills their obligations before the funds are released.\n\nIt's important to note that the specific procedures and remedies available may vary depending on the terms of the escrow agreement and the laws of the jurisdiction in which the transaction is taking place. It's always a good idea to review the escrow agreement and consult with a legal professional if you have any concerns about the escrow process or potential disputes.",
